---
export const prerender = true;
import BlogLayout from '../../layouts/BlogLayout.astro';
import '../../styles/global.css';
---

<BlogLayout
  title="Advanced Hook Words in Scrabble — Beyond Simple S-Hooks"
  description="Master advanced hooking: front hooks, surprising back hooks, multi-letter extensions, and the rare hooks that catch opponents off guard. Examples with scoring impact."
  keywords="advanced hooks scrabble, front hook words, surprising hooks, scrabble word extensions, hook strategy advanced, rare hooks scrabble, multi-letter hooks"
>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "Advanced Hook Words in Scrabble — Beyond Simple S-Hooks",
    "description": "Master advanced hooking: front hooks, surprising back hooks, multi-letter extensions, and the rare hooks that catch opponents off guard. Examples with scoring impact.",
    "datePublished": "2026-06-15",
    "author": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "ScrabbleWordsFinder.com", "url": "https://www.scrabblewordsfinder.com" },
    "publisher": { "@type": "Organization", "name": "ScrabbleWordsFinder.com" },
    "mainEntityOfPage": { "@type": "WebPage", "@id": "https://www.scrabblewordsfinder.com/blog/hook-words-advanced" }
  })} />

  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={JSON.stringify({
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What makes a hook 'advanced' in Scrabble?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "An advanced hook goes beyond the obvious S-plural or D-past-tense. It includes unexpected front hooks (like H+EAR making HEAR, B+RASH making BRASH), surprising back hooks that change a word's meaning (TIN+E making TINE, HOS+T making HOST), and multi-letter extensions using prefixes like UN- or RE-. These hooks are harder to spot and more difficult for opponents to block." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How do front hooks differ from back hooks strategically?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "Front hooks are placed before an existing word (S+LAUGHTER = SLAUGHTER), while back hooks go after (GAME+R = GAMER). Front hooks are strategically stronger because opponents rarely anticipate them — most players only check word endings. However, back hooks offer more raw options since English has more suffixes than prefixes. Advanced players study both equally." }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What percentage of tournament Scrabble plays involve hooks?",
        "acceptedAnswer": { "@type": "Answer", "text": "In competitive Scrabble, approximately 35-40% of all plays involve some form of hooking. Advanced players use hooks even more frequently — top-tier tournament players report that hooks contribute to roughly 45% of their scoring turns. This includes both simple S-hooks and advanced front/multi-letter hooks that create parallel scoring opportunities." }
      }
    ]
  })} />

  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 py-12">
    <article class="prose prose-invert prose-gray max-w-none">
      <nav class="text-sm text-gray-400 mb-6 not-prose flex items-center gap-1">
        <a href="/blog/" class="hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors">← Blog</a>
        <span class="mx-1">›</span>
        <a href="/blog/strategy/" class="hover:text-blue-400 transition-colors text-gray-300">Strategy</a>
      </nav>

      <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-4">Advanced Hook Words in Scrabble — Beyond Simple S-Hooks</h1>

      <div class="not-prose mb-8 flex items-center gap-3 text-sm text-gray-400">
        <time datetime="2026-06-15">June 15, 2026</time>
        <span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-gray-600"></span>
        <span>6 min read</span>
        <span class="w-1 h-1 rounded-full bg-gray-600"></span>
        <a href="/" class="inline-flex items-center gap-1 text-blue-400 hover:underline"><span aria-hidden="true">🔤</span> Word Finder</a>
      </div>

      <p class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-gray-300 mb-8">
        Every Scrabble player knows you can add S to pluralize words. That's hooking 101. But the players who dominate tournaments have gone far deeper — they know front hooks that transform common words into unexpected ones, back hooks that defy intuition, and multi-letter extensions that turn short words into bingos. This guide takes you beyond basic hooks and into the territory where real board control happens.
      </p>

      <!-- Hero Card -->
      <div class="not-prose my-8 p-6 rounded-2xl border-2 border-amber-500/50 bg-gradient-to-r from-amber-950/30 to-yellow-950/20 relative overflow-hidden">
        <div class="absolute top-3 right-4 text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-widest text-amber-500/70">👑 Core Concept</div>
        <p class="text-2xl font-black text-white tracking-wider mb-2">ONE LETTER = TWO WORDS</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-amber-300 font-semibold mb-3">Every hook scores twice — the modified word + your perpendicular play</p>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">Advanced hooks exploit this mechanic to its fullest. While beginners add S for 2 extra points, experts use rare front hooks and surprise extensions to generate 30-50 point plays from a single tile placement. The key is knowing which hooks exist that your opponent doesn't.</p>
      </div>

      <!-- Stat Strip -->
      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-amber-500/30 bg-amber-950/10">
        <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center justify-center gap-6 text-center">
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">~40%</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Tournament plays use hooks</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">25%</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Words accept front hooks</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">80%+</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Words accept back hooks</p></div>
          <div><p class="text-xl font-bold text-amber-400">50+ pts</p><p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Top hook play value</p></div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Front Hooks — The Underused Weapon</h2>

      <p>Front hooks add a letter before an existing word. Most players obsess over word endings, so front-hook opportunities sit unclaimed turn after turn. The element of surprise alone makes front hooks worth studying — opponents won't block what they can't see coming.</p>

      <div class="overflow-x-auto not-prose my-6">
        <table class="w-full text-sm border border-gray-700 rounded-lg overflow-hidden shadow-sm">
          <thead class="bg-gray-800">
            <tr>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-300">Hook Letter</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-300">Original Word</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-300">New Word</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-300">Why It Surprises</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-800">
            <tr class="bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-blue-400 font-bold">H</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white">EAR</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">HEAR</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Common word, rarely spotted as hookable</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-blue-400 font-bold">B</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white">RASH</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">BRASH</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Adjective from adjective — unintuitive</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-blue-400 font-bold">S</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white">LAUGHTER</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">SLAUGHTER</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Meaning completely transforms</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-blue-400 font-bold">W</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white">ITCH</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">WITCH</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Short words open multiple front hooks</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-blue-400 font-bold">G</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white">RIPE</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">GRIPE</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Different word class entirely</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-blue-400 font-bold">T</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white">ESTER</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">TESTER</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Agent noun from archaic base</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-blue-400 font-bold">C</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white">HARM</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">CHARM</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Positive word from negative one</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-blue-400 font-bold">P</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white">LACE</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">PLACE</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">High-frequency word, low hook awareness</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">💡 Front Hook Pattern</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200">The most productive front-hook letters are <span class="text-white font-medium">S, C, B, T, W, P, and G</span>. Short words (3-4 letters) starting with vowels are the most hookable from the front because consonant + vowel combinations frequently form valid words.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Surprise Back Hooks — Beyond Plurals</h2>

      <p>Everyone knows GAME+S. The real scoring edge comes from back hooks that don't follow obvious patterns — adding a letter that transforms the word into something entirely different rather than just inflecting it.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">🔤 Meaning-Shifting Hooks</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">TIN + E → TINE (a prong) • HOS + T → HOST (completely new word) • GAM + E → GAME • SIN + E → SINE (trigonometry) • RAP + T → RAPT (absorbed)</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-cyan-500/30 bg-cyan-950/10">
          <p class="text-cyan-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">🔤 Extension Hooks</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">GAMER + S → GAMERS • GAME + R → GAMER • HOST + S → HOSTS • PINE + S → PINES • LEMON + Y → LEMONY</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="overflow-x-auto not-prose my-6">
        <table class="w-full text-sm border border-gray-700 rounded-lg overflow-hidden shadow-sm">
          <thead class="bg-gray-800">
            <tr>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-300">Base Word</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-300">Hook</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-300">Result</th>
              <th class="px-4 py-3 text-left font-semibold text-gray-300">Surprise Factor</th>
            </tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-800">
            <tr class="bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white">TIN</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-green-400 font-bold">E</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">TINE</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">New meaning — fork prong</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white">HOS</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-green-400 font-bold">T</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">HOST</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Common word from obscure base</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white">RAP</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-green-400 font-bold">T</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">RAPT</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Adjective from verb — unintuitive</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white">SIN</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-green-400 font-bold">E</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">SINE</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Mathematical term from common word</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white">PLAN</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-green-400 font-bold">E</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">PLANE</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Meaning shifts dramatically</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-800/50"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white">WINE</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-green-400 font-bold">D</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">WINED</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Verb form most players don't know</td></tr>
            <tr class="bg-gray-900"><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white">LING</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-green-400 font-bold">O</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-white font-medium">LINGO</td><td class="px-4 py-3 text-gray-400">Complete meaning shift with O</td></tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-blue-500/30 bg-blue-950/20">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-blue-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">💡 Scoring Insight</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200">Surprise hooks are especially powerful because opponents <span class="text-white font-medium">don't anticipate them</span>. If your opponent plays TIN near a Triple Word Score, they probably think it's safe. Adding E to make TINE while playing your own high-scoring word perpendicular catches them completely off guard — and you get the TWS bonus on both words.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Multi-Letter Hooks — Prefix & Suffix Extensions</h2>

      <p>Standard hooks add one letter. Multi-letter hooks extend a word by two or more letters at once using common prefixes (UN-, RE-, OUT-, OVER-) or suffixes (-ING, -TION, -NESS). These aren't technically single-letter hooks, but they leverage the same board mechanic — building off existing words to score big.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/10">
          <p class="text-purple-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">🔗 Prefix Extensions (Front)</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">UN + DONE → UNDONE • RE + PLAY → REPLAY • OUT + SCORE → OUTSCORE • OVER + PLAY → OVERPLAY • MIS + PLAY → MISPLAY</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/10">
          <p class="text-purple-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">🔗 Suffix Extensions (Back)</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">HOOK + ING → HOOKING • SCORE + LESS → SCORELESS • PLAY + FUL → PLAYFUL • WORD + SMITH → WORDSMITH</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/10">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-purple-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">🧩 Multi-Hook Spotting Process</p>
        <div class="space-y-3">
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">1</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">Scan the board for words that accept common prefixes — look for DONE, PLAY, TIE, SET, DO, WIND, TURN, MAKE</p>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">2</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">Check if you have the prefix tiles on your rack (U+N, R+E, O+U+T) — multi-hooks need 2-4 tiles committed</p>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">3</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">Verify there's open space before/after the target word — you need 2-4 empty squares in a row</p>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">4</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">Check all perpendicular crossings — each tile you place creates a new 2-letter word with adjacent tiles. All must be valid.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="flex items-start gap-3">
            <span class="shrink-0 w-6 h-6 rounded-full bg-purple-900/50 border border-purple-500/40 flex items-center justify-center text-xs text-purple-300 font-bold">5</span>
            <p class="text-sm text-gray-300">Calculate total score — multi-hooks often score 30-50+ because you're scoring the full extended word plus any perpendicular crosses</p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Dig Deeper cross-links -->
      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-4 rounded-xl border border-indigo-500/30 bg-indigo-950/10">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-indigo-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-3">📚 Dig Deeper</p>
        <div class="grid gap-2">
          <a href="/blog/hooking-existing-words/" class="flex items-center gap-2 p-2 rounded-lg hover:bg-indigo-900/20 transition-all group">
            <span class="text-indigo-400 group-hover:translate-x-0.5 transition-transform shrink-0">→</span>
            <span class="text-sm text-gray-300 group-hover:text-indigo-300 transition-colors">Hooking Existing Words — foundational techniques for single-letter hooks</span>
          </a>
          <a href="/blog/complete-guide-to-hooks/" class="flex items-center gap-2 p-2 rounded-lg hover:bg-indigo-900/20 transition-all group">
            <span class="text-indigo-400 group-hover:translate-x-0.5 transition-transform shrink-0">→</span>
            <span class="text-sm text-gray-300 group-hover:text-indigo-300 transition-colors">Complete Guide to Hooks — master front hooks and back hooks from scratch</span>
          </a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Defensive Anti-Hook Play</h2>

      <p>Knowing hooks isn't just offensive — it's essential for defense. If you understand which words are easily hooked, you can avoid playing them near premium squares where opponents can exploit them.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-green-500/30 bg-green-950/10">
          <p class="text-green-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">✓ Offensive Hooking</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Play words near premium squares that YOU can hook next turn. Create setups where you benefit from the hook on your following move. Leave hookable words adjacent to TWS only when you have the hook letter on your rack.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-red-500/30 bg-red-950/10">
          <p class="text-red-400 font-semibold text-sm mb-1">✗ Defensive Anti-Hook</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-gray-400">Never play highly hookable words (those accepting S, E, D, R) next to premium squares you can't control. Choose hook-resistant words ending in V, J, C, or Q near danger zones. Block by pre-hooking before your opponent can.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Pre-emptive hooking:</span> If you spot a word your opponent could hook near a TWS, hook it yourself first with a modest play. You score some points AND deny them the big opportunity. Even a 10-point pre-emptive hook that prevents a 40-point opponent play is a 30-point swing.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Hook-resistant endings:</span> Words ending in -VE, -IC, -AJ, or -OX are very difficult to hook with a single letter. When protecting a lead late in the game, choose these endings near premium squares to lock down the board.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Create dead ends:</span> Play words that fill space without creating new hook opportunities. A word placed tight against the edge of the board with no open squares before or after it is essentially unhookable — there's nowhere to put the hook letter.</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 p-5 rounded-xl border border-cyan-500/30 bg-cyan-950/10">
        <p class="text-sm font-semibold text-cyan-400 uppercase tracking-wider mb-2">🎯 Parallel Play Scoring with Hooks</p>
        <p class="text-base text-gray-200">The ultimate advanced hook technique: play a word <span class="text-white font-medium">parallel to an existing word</span> so that every tile in your word creates a valid two-letter combination with the tiles below or above. A 5-letter parallel play can score for 6 words simultaneously — your main word plus 5 two-letter crossings. Combined with a front or back hook on the parallel word itself, this generates 40-70 point plays routinely at tournament level.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 class="text-xl font-light text-blue-400 mt-10 mb-4 border-l-4 border-blue-400 pl-4">Studying Hooks for Competitive Play</h2>

      <p>Tournament players don't memorize hooks randomly. They use systematic approaches to build hook knowledge in the order that gives the biggest competitive return.</p>

      <div class="not-prose my-6 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4">
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Start with high-frequency hooks:</span> Learn which 3-4 letter words accept the most hooks. Words like ATE (accepts 8+ front hooks: B, D, F, G, H, L, M, R, S), OAT (B, C, G, M), and RAIN (B, D, G, T, S) appear constantly in games.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Memorize E-hooks on 3-letter words:</span> Adding E to short words is surprisingly productive. TIN→TINE, GAM→GAME, HOP→HOPE, PAN→PANE, SIN→SINE, FAT→FATE, MAT→MATE. These E-hooks shift meanings and catch opponents flat-footed.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Learn the S front-hook list:</span> S before a word is the sneakiest front hook. LAUGHTER→SLAUGHTER, CAT→SCAT, HONE→SHONE, NAIL→SNAIL, COLD→SCOLD, PARK→SPARK. These transform familiar words into unexpected ones.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
          <p class="text-sm text-gray-300"><span class="text-purple-400 font-semibold">Practice with a word finder:</span> Use our Scrabble Word Finder to verify hooks in real-time during practice games. Type the base word, then test with each possible hook letter to build your mental database of valid extensions.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="p-4 rounded-xl border border-purple-500/30 bg-purple-950/20 hover:border-purple-400 transition-colors">
